<Document>
<name>Gotthard Pass via the Tremola</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Gotthard Pass via the Tremola</h2><p><i>Ticino / Uri, Switzerland · Bellinzona to Andermatt over the St Gotthard</i></p><p><b>13th-century cobblestoned hairpins beside the modern motorway tunnel — 700 years of Alpine crossing.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>68 km (42 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>3 hrs</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>Late May–October</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Wet cobblestones slippery, many cyclists, weather, A2 motorway tunnel queues nearby</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>161</td></tr></table><hr><p>The Gotthard was the most important Alpine crossing between southern Europe and the German-speaking lands for 700 years. Modern A2 plunges through the mountain in a 17 km tunnel; the old road over the top is yours. The Tremola — 4 km of 13th-century stone-paved switchbacks on 38 numbered hairpins — is the oldest still-used cobbled pass road in the Alps. UNESCO has recognized it. Drive it in dry weather; the polished stones get slippery when wet. Bellinzona's three medieval castles at the southern end of the route are also UNESCO listed. Wear a jacket: the summit can drop below freezing in August.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Bellinzona castles</b> — Three medieval castles (Castelgrande, Montebello, Sasso Corbaro) on the strategic neck of the Ticino valley. UNESCO World Heritage; walk the connecting walls.</li><li><b>Tremola — old cobbled road</b> — 4 km of 13th-century stone pavement on 38 numbered hairpins. Drive slowly; stop on the stones for the photograph that defines the climb.</li><li><b>Passo del San Gottardo</b> — 2,106 m. Pilgrim hospice founded 1230s. Museum on the pass about 800 years of Alpine traffic; restaurant. Italian/German linguistic frontier crosses this summit.</li><li><b>Hospental</b> — 13th-century medieval tower of the Lords of Hospental, who controlled the pass. The village sits at the junction of the Furka, Gotthard, and Oberalp routes.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
